## Summary

  Streaming methods (`post_stream`, `post_stream_mapped_raw_events`, `get_stream`) return `Ok(stream)` even when the HTTP response status is non-2xx. The `OpenAIError::ApiError` is then delivered as the **first item of the returned stream**, not as the `Err` of the calling function. Callers that want HTTP failures surfaced as function-level errors (the natural Rust shape: `Result<Stream, Error>`) have to peek the first item themselves and prepend it back if it's a valid chunk.

  ## Where it happens

  `execute_stream` ([`src/client.rs#L638-L647`](https://github.com/64bit/async-openai/blob/main/async-openai/src/client.rs)) calls `execute_response().await?` and then unconditionally constructs the stream, regardless of status:

```rust
  async fn execute_stream<O>(...) -> Result<StreamResponse<O>, OpenAIError> {
      let response = self.execute_response(request_factory).await?;
      Ok(stream(response).await)   // <-- always Ok, even for 4xx/5xx
  }
```

  The status check is deferred into stream_mapped_raw_events, which on a bad status emits the error as the first stream item:

  - wasm path (src/client.rs#L775-L784):
```rust
  if !response.status().is_success() {
      return Box::pin(futures::stream::once(async move {
          match read_response(response).await {
              Ok(_) => Err(OpenAIError::InvalidArgument(...)),
              Err(error) => Err(error),
          }
      }));
  }
```
  - non-wasm path (src/client.rs#L831-L839):
```rust
  tokio::spawn(async move {
      if !response.status().is_success() {
          if let Err(e) = read_response(response).await {
              let _ = tx.send(Err(e));
          }
          return;
      }
      ...
  });
```

  ## Reproducer (conceptual)

  Any streaming call against a server that returns 400/401/etc.:

```rust
  let stream_result = client.chat().create_stream(bad_request).await;
  // stream_result is Ok(_), not Err(OpenAIError::ApiError(...))
  let mut stream = stream_result.unwrap();
  let first = stream.next().await;
  // first is Some(Err(OpenAIError::ApiError(...)))
```

  ## Why this matters

  For gateway / proxy callers (and any code that wants to short-circuit on HTTP failure before consuming a stream), the current shape forces a peek-and-prepend workaround at every call site:

```rust
  match stream.next().await {
      Some(Err(e)) => Err(e),
      Some(Ok(first)) => Ok(Box::pin(stream::once(async move { Ok(first) }).chain(stream))),
      None => Err(empty_stream_error()),
  }
```

  This is also surprising for new users — the natural Rust expectation is that Result<Stream, Error> distinguishes "couldn't open the stream" from "stream item failed." Today both collapse to Ok(stream_that_yields_err).

  ## Proposed change

  Check the response status inside execute_stream / execute_stream_mapped_raw_events and return Err(...) directly when non-2xx, before constructing the stream. The body parsing logic already exists in read_response (src/client.rs#L726-L752) — it just needs to be invoked from the streaming path on the non-2xx branch.

  ## Rough sketch:

```rust
  async fn execute_stream<O>(...) -> Result<StreamResponse<O>, OpenAIError> {
      let response = self.execute_response(request_factory).await?;
      if !response.status().is_success() {
          // Reuse read_response — already handles both JSON-bodied and raw 5xx error paths.
          let _ = read_response(response).await?;
          return Err(OpenAIError::InvalidArgument(
              "stream request failed without an error body".into(),
          ));
      }
      Ok(stream(response).await)
  }
```

  This is a breaking change for any caller that today relies on the error arriving as a stream item, but the new shape is strictly more informative (you can still get the item-style error by collecting from the stream if you want; the function-level error is the new option).

  Happy to send a PR if there's agreement on the approach.

OpenAI will sometimes emit `response.output_item.added` events for web searches before the `action` details are populated. This in turn causes an error from `async-openai` as it expects the action field to exist. The payload we've seen come back from OpenAI looks like:

```json
{
  "type": "response.output_item.added",
  "sequence_number": 2,
  "output_index": 0,
  "item": {
    "id": "ws_123",
    "type": "web_search_call",
    "status": "in_progress"
  }
}
```

The lifecycle shape of these events seems to be a bit looser than the final streaming shape. The openai docs describe `web_search_call` with idd, action, status, and type, but this doesn't seem accurate for in-progress events. OpenAIs own SDKs seem to have matching reports for this as well: 
- https://github.com/openai/openai-java/issues/633
  - https://github.com/openai/openai-java/issues/600
- https://github.com/openai/openai-python/issues/2448 

This behavior tested on `async-openai: 0.34.0`. 

